[Interesting that "5 US states have nearly 50% of cases (NY, MI, Fl, PA, NJ) but those states do not overlap cleanly with the states that have the highest prevalence of B117 or other variants of concern in the US (CA, CO, MN, MI, NH, FL) as shown to us by this CDC map (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/transmission/variant-cases.html). ...each state's cases probably reflective of their natural immunity (high in CA, TX after 3rd surge; low in MI as not as large surges) + vaccination rate," tweeted Monica Gandhi (https://threadreaderapp.com/thread/1379661028041007106.html). Thus, B.1.1.7 may not signify a dire situation ahead. The total picture must be taken into account, including the variant's increased transmissibility, degree of increased virulence, and how well it can escape immunity from your vaccine (or natural infection). - Mod.LK]

[The source of primary data to support the statement, that B.1.1.7 is "now the most common lineage circulating in the United States," is not immediately apparent. The CDC table of U.S. COVID-19 cases caused by variants shows 19,554 cases of B.1.1.7 reported as of April 8 https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/transmission/variant-cases.html, and thus the total number of reported B.1.1.7 cases reported thus far is only about one-fourth of the current rough number of new daily cases of COVID-19 in the U.S.A.

One source of quantitative tracking of circulating COVID variants is the CoVariants website https://covariants.org, based on GISAID data https://www.gisaid.org/, which has very useful information about many variants of interest, including a list of the defining mutations, links to publications, distribution by country, and 3D protein models. For B.1.1.7, see https://covariants.org/variants/S.501Y.V1. For the U.S.A., B.1.1.7 (also called 501Y.V1) was in fact the most common strain sequence for the week of 22 Mar 2021, constituting 34% of a total of 927 GISAID sequences https://covariants.org/per-country. One caveat about these variant sequence data is that they are based on sequences submitted to GISAID, so they are not a random sampling and are based on a limited number of sequences, the number of which varies significantly from week to week. As stated on the CoVariants per-country webpage, "It's important not to assume frequencies shown are necessarily representative of the country." -Mod.LXL]

