[4] Chile: surge in cases
Date: Tue 6 Apr 2021 08:52 EDT
Source: El Pais [in Spanish, translated and summarized by Pablo Nart Peñalver, edited]
https://elpais.com/sociedad/2021-04-06/por-que-los-casos-de-covid-19-son-record-en-chile-cuando-el-pais-tiene-el-45-de-su-poblacion-vacunada.html


Chile is going through the worst time of the pandemic, with more than 8000 daily infections in recent days and a record of ICU occupancy, despite that 45% of the population, 7 of the 19 million inhabitants, have received at least a dose of the vaccine, according to the latest data provided by the Minister of Health, Enrique Paris. This wave has been higher than the peak of the 1st wave registered in June [2020] and growing much more quickly. An excess of public confidence, derived from the rapid vaccination campaign, and that the new variants were already present at the time of the vaccination campaign are singled as possible causes for the increase in cases.

"...Last year [2020] it took us 3 months to climb the hill and now we have reached the same point, even higher, in just a month," says Gabriel Cavada, biostatistician at the School of Public Health of the University of Chile. "We are climbing it too fast, 3 times as much, according to the charts," he adds.

"Only the positive aspects of the campaign have been highlighted but not the dangers that remain," analyses the doctor Mauricio Canals, a member of the ICOVID platform, an initiative led by the University of Chile, the Pontificia Universidad Catolica de Chile and the Universidad de Concepcion, based on official data...he lists the factors that would have caused the new wave. "After the summer [2020], in March [2021] the activities began with practically no restrictions. Quarantines were never effective, population mobility increased considerably." With the opening of schools and shopping centers, in his opinion, the wrong message was delivered to the public.

The Chilean Executive managed to stock up on vaccines like no other country in the region and, thanks to its strong primary health system, it has been able to deploy a speedy campaign and one of the most successful in the world. But it has not been able to stop the infections: in 13 months, they exceed one million and there are currently 2883 admitted to ICUs, the maximum in the pandemic, with only 164 critical beds available nationwide.

Doctor Canals added: "The (vaccine-induced) immune status...has not covered the population that is transmitting the disease, which is between 30 and 60 years. It is a group that is just beginning to have a little immunity these days"...(that's why), the age of the people who occupy the ICU beds has been changing. Today [6 Apr 2021], according to official data, there are more hospitalized between 40 and 49 years (469), than those over 70 (378). The latter slightly outnumber the youngest (359 admitted under the age of 39). But the fatality rate has not decreased and remains at 2.4%.... "Unlike the 1st wave of 2020, when younger people with severe courses of the disease enter the ICU, they spend more time in the complex bed and the ventilator."

Projections made by Gabriel Cavada (for the current surge) warn of the possibility of reaching up to 300 000 new infections. "As we climb this hill so fast, my hope is that the descent will also be fast, but I have no evidence to support it," he explains.

(At present) Chile has 23 677 deaths confirmed by PCR, although the Ministry of Health reports 31 151 probable deaths without laboratory confirmation of the diagnosis. "Is a terrible situation, the number deaths confirmed by PCR could reach between 30 000 and 35 000 (persons)," explains the epidemiologist, while the non PCR-confirmed "could reach about 45 000" [resulting in a ratio between 163 and 237 deaths per 100 000 habitants; for comparison the UK ratio stands at 190. - PNP].

[Byline: Rocio Montes]

--
Communicated by:
Pablo Nart Peñalver
<pablo.n.penalver@gmail.com>

[The above article was kindly submitted to ProMED by Pablo Nart Peñalver (initials PNP) in response to a recent post concerning COVID-19 in Chile (COVID-19 update (119): Chile, indoor transmission risk, WHO, global 20210331.8281129), in which Mod.LM commented "Chile represents a good case study showing that widespread vaccination at modest levels, similar to that now seen in the US, do not by themselves prevent surging COVID-19 cases." Dr. Nart Peñalver also provides the following additional articles with commentary:

A recent paper by Moore et al. (Vaccination and non-pharmaceutical interventions for COVID-19: a mathematical modelling study. Lancet Infect Dis. https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(21)00143-2/fulltext) calculating the impact of vaccination against SARS-CoV-2 in the UK reported that there's still the possibility to get very many hospitalisations and deaths even if vaccine uptake and efficacy were highly significant.

In their findings the authors say: "We estimate that vaccination alone is insufficient to contain the outbreak. In the absence of NPIs (non-pharmaceutical interventions), even with our most optimistic assumption that the vaccine will prevent 85% of infections, we estimate R to be 1.58 (95% credible intervals [CI] 1.36-1.84) once all eligible adults have been offered both doses of the vaccine. Under the default uptake scenario, removal of all NPIs once the vaccination programme is complete is predicted to lead to 21  400 deaths (95% CI 1400-55  100) due to COVID-19."

Similar predictions, if restrictions are lifted too quickly, were published in February 2021 by the Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies, a British Government advisory body. The following is abridged from The New European, authored by Jonathan Read (https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/brexit-news/westminster-news/coronavirus-lockdown-lifting-7659572):

"SAGE scientists fear 'fresh wave' of coronavirus cases by July: Summarising what the papers show, the government's chief scientific adviser Sir Patrick Vallance said: 'The modelling lays out a series of scenarios. None of them are the precise ones which the government ultimately decided to go for, but they lie between those options and that's the point of the modelling to lay out scenarios, not to point to a single answer.'

"He continued: 'Vaccines are predicted -- as you'd expect and hope -- to make a big difference.'

"Professor Dame Angela McLean, chief scientific adviser for the Ministry of Defence, added: 'If you unlock more slowly, the peak that you get is less high. And I think all of us feel that would be a good thing. It's common sense why that happens, there remain people who have either been not vaccinated, or even though these vaccines are absolutely fantastic, they are not perfect -- so there are people who have been vaccinated who nevertheless are not protected from very severe disease. So if we're to let a big epidemic happen among younger people, then some of those vulnerable older people, or people who are vulnerable for another reason, will get infected and will become very ill.'

"In a Scientific Pandemic Influenza Group on Modelling (SPI-M) document dated 17 Feb 2021, modelling by the University of Warwick and Imperial College London is set out and says that even under the most optimistic set of assumptions, at least a further 30 000 Covid-19 deaths could occur. Under some of the models, such as with a rapid relaxation of rules, further death figures would reach well over 100 000.

"It continues: 'There is the potential for a resurgence to result in a very large number of infections (3rd wave) if restrictions are lifted early or rapidly which would lead to large numbers of hospitalisations and deaths unless vaccine coverage is very high.'"

Dr. Nart Peñalver writes in conclusion, "It is thus likely that we may need to learn to live with a significant degree of mortality and morbidity among those unvaccinated or not totally protected by the vaccines, unless stricter non pharmaceutical interventions are considered feasible or desirable." -Mod.LXL]

