Communicated by:
Dan Silver
<dgsilver@gmail.com>

[According to the situation report of the China National Health Commission dated 8 Apr 2021, from 0-24:00 on 7 Apr 2021, there were 11 local cases in China, all in Yunnan http://www.nhc.gov.cn/xcs/yqtb/202104/ed07471bac3946ce8f2c0e5ea1901173.shtml. Yunnan province has a disproportionately high number of the total current COVID-19 cases in China. Yunnan is also where the bat coronavirus that is most closely related to the SARS-CoV-2 was identified several years before the COVID-19 pandemic. Finally, Yunnan is one of the main provinces where wildlife animal farming (of minks, fox, raccoon dogs, and others) has been promoted. The article above says that the 8 new cases were all detected in Ruili City employees; if these tests were performed as part of routine screening, it would suggest that there may be many more cases in the community. Ruili is in the westernmost part of Yunnan, bordering Burma (in fact, it was a waystation on the historic Burma Road), and has a large population of Dai and other ethnic minority groups (sometimes called "hill tribes"), and presumably sees relatively more cross-border traffic. -Mod.LXL]

